ol in some measurable way.    There is no compelling reasoning by the author here.  It makes as much sense as someone buying a Chevrolet that they believe is an inferior automobile.  They prefer the Ford, believe it will give them better service, is safer etc., but reason that if they buy a Chevy then GMC will have more money and thus will be able to put more resources into engineering and building a better car sometime down the road.  Nuts! "/><type4:DocumentMetaData xmi:id="13" sofa="1" begin="0" end="753" language="en" documentId="2643" isLastSegment="false"/><types:WebArgumentMetadata xmi:id="24" sofa="1" begin="0" end="0" author="Ducksfanman" date="Aug 29, 2013 8:34PM" docType="artcomment" origUrl="http://living.msn.com/family-parenting/the-family-room-blog-post?post=ab228ffc-1e99-4b37-a7b8-0b6a4c3fb240" topic="public-private-schools" thumbsUp="6" thumbsDown="0" origId="2643" notes="" title="Is it wrong to send kids to private school?"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="39" sofa="1" begin="0" end="753"/><cas:View sofa="1" members="13 24 39"/></xmi:XMI>